@@eThe Arroyo -- Trade Syndic Comparative Law File@@N

The Arroyo is a dry canyon in the distant eastern desert. The @@yTrade
Syndics@@N maintain a file on it as a @@Wjurisdictional case study@@N --
because it demonstrates what happens when you build law atop law
without clearing the foundations.

Five historical layers remain active simultaneously. @@yKeeper-era@@N
measurement: thirst oaths, silt tallies, witness stones. @@ySalt
Ledger@@N extraction: toll courts, confiscation vaults, mortuary intake
for those who died in arrears -- @@d"unpaid names"@@N whose rites were
withheld pending debt settlement. @@dPyramid jurisdiction@@N reframing
debt default as spiritual trespass. @@rSynod coercion@@N where
authorized thirst became prayer and threat. And @@gecological
takeover@@N: scorpions nesting through ossuary chambers.

Each regime carved atop the previous inscriptions. No regime cleared
the stone first. @@rLaw atop law atop law, with no foundation
visible.@@N

The Syndics draw three lessons for Kiess governance.

First: @@ythe unpaid name precedent.@@N The Salt Ledger Kingdoms
withheld burial from debtors -- the same mechanism as Midgaard's
@@ddeferred names@@N. Obligation sealed against the dead, accumulating
without expiration. Kiess prohibits this explicitly. A debt dies
with the debtor unless a living party assumes it by witnessed
compact. No warrant against the voiceless.

Second: @@ythe palimpsest problem.@@N When Kiess inherited Evermeet's
foundations, Three-Power Governance deliberately acknowledged the
old city through memorial waystones but built @@ynew law on cleared
ground@@N. Evermeet's ordinances were read, recorded, and formally
@@rextinguished@@N. The Arroyo shows what happens when you skip that
step -- ambiguity compounds into chaos.

Third: @@ythe ecological warning.@@N The canyon's oldest infrastructure
is now @@rinfested@@N. Scorpion broods in assessment chambers. Resin in
record halls. When institutions abandon space, the space does not
stay neutral. @@dWall Command@@N applies this to our northern perimeter:
every bell-post lost to the mist becomes @@rhostile@@N territory.

The @@dDustbound Court-Dead@@N -- former assessors still demanding
declarations -- are process outliving purpose. The canyon remembers
every court that sat there, and every court that failed.

@@yThe Prism records@@N: clear your foundations or your foundations will
bury you. The Arroyo carved that lesson in stone five times over,
and no one who carved it could read what came before.
